**Comparison Table:**

| Aspect | SVG | Canvas |
|--------|-----|--------|
| **Type** | Vector-based (XML) | Raster-based (Pixels) |
| **Scalability** | Scales to any size without losing quality | Pixelates when scaled up |
| **DOM Integration** | Each shape is a DOM element | Single DOM element |
| **Interactivity** | CSS and JS can target individual elements | Manual hit detection required |
| **Performance** | Good for simple graphics, slower with many elements | Fast for complex scenes and animations |
| **Memory Usage** | Higher with many elements | Lower, fixed per canvas |
| **Search/Accessibility** | Text is searchable and accessible | Content not accessible to screen readers |
| **Styling** | CSS styling supported | Styling via JavaScript/Canvas API |
| **File Size** | Larger for complex graphics | Smaller file size |
| **Browser Support** | IE9+ (with polyfills for older) | All modern browsers |

**When to Use SVG:**
- â Logos and icons
- â Simple illustrations and diagrams
- â Interactive data visualizations
- â Scalable graphics for responsive design
- â When you need CSS styling and animations
- â Accessibility is important
- â Print-quality graphics

**When to Use Canvas:**
- â Games and real-time animations
- â Image editing and manipulation
- â Complex data visualizations with many data points
- â Performance-critical applications
- â Pixel-level image processing
- â Charts and graphs with thousands of data points
- â WebGL 3D graphics

**Code Examples Summary:**
- **SVG**: Declarative, XML-based, each element is interactive
- **Canvas**: Imperative, JavaScript-based, single drawing surface
- **Performance**: Canvas better for many elements, SVG better for few interactive elements
- **Accessibility**: SVG has built-in accessibility, Canvas requires additional work

