**5. Performance Considerations:**

```css
/* Use transform and opacity for best performance */
.good-performance {
  /* These properties are GPU accelerated */
  transform: translateX(100px);
  opacity: 0.5;
  transition: transform 0.3s, opacity 0.3s;
}

/* Avoid animating these properties (causes reflows) */
.poor-performance {
  /* These cause layout recalculations */
  width: 200px;
  height: 100px;
  margin-left: 50px;
  transition: width 0.3s, height 0.3s, margin-left 0.3s;
}

/* Use will-change for complex animations */
.complex-animation {
  will-change: transform, opacity;
  /* Remove will-change when animation completes */
}
```

**6. Animation Control with JavaScript:**

```css
/* CSS classes for JavaScript control */
.paused { animation-play-state: paused; }
.playing { animation-play-state: running; }
.reverse { animation-direction: reverse; }

/* Animation event classes */
.animate-in {
  animation: fadeIn 0.5s ease-out forwards;
}

.animate-out {
  animation: fadeOut 0.5s ease-in forwards;
}

@keyframes fadeOut {
  from {
    opacity: 1;
    transform: scale(1);
  }
  to {
    opacity: 0;
    transform: scale(0.9);
  }
}
```

**Best Practices:**
1. **Use transform and opacity** for best performance
2. **Keep animations under 300ms** for micro-interactions
3. **Use ease-out** for entrances, **ease-in** for exits
4. **Respect prefers-reduced-motion** for accessibility
5. **Test on slower devices** to ensure smooth performance

**Advantages of CSS:**

| Advantage | Description | Benefit |
|-----------|-------------|----------|
| **Separation of Concerns** | Separates content (HTML) from presentation (CSS) | Cleaner, maintainable code |
| **Consistency** | One stylesheet for multiple pages | Uniform design across site |
| **Maintainability** | Update styles in one place | Easy site-wide changes |
| **Performance** | External stylesheets are cached | Faster subsequent page loads |
| **Flexibility** | Multiple designs for same content | Easy theme switching |
| **Accessibility** | Better control over presentation | Improved user experience |

**Example demonstrating advantages:**

```css
/* styles.css - One file for entire website */
:root {
  --primary-color: #007bff;
  --font-family: 'Arial', sans-serif;
}

.button {
  background-color: var(--primary-color);
  font-family: var(--font-family);
  padding: 10px 20px;
  border: none;
  border-radius: 5px;
  color: white;
  cursor: pointer;
}

.button:hover {
  background-color: #0056b3;
}

/* Media query for responsiveness */
@media (max-width: 768px) {
  .button {
    padding: 8px 16px;
    font-size: 14px;
  }
}
```

```html
<!-- Multiple pages can use the same styles -->
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
  <link rel="stylesheet" href="styles.css">
</head>
<body>
  <button class="button">Click Me</button>
  <button class="button">Another Button</button>
</body>
</html>
```

**Benefits in Action:**
- **Consistency**: All buttons look the same across pages
- **Maintainability**: Change `--primary-color` once, updates everywhere
- **Performance**: CSS file cached after first load
- **Responsiveness**: Automatic mobile optimization

**CSS Limitations:**

| Limitation | Description | Impact |
|------------|-------------|--------|
| **Browser Compatibility** | Different interpretations across browsers | Need vendor prefixes, fallbacks |
| **No Parent Selector** | Can't select parent based on child | Limited styling options |
| **No Logic/Variables** | No programming constructs | Repetitive code (partly solved with CSS variables) |
| **Specificity Conflicts** | Complex inheritance rules | Hard to debug style conflicts |
| **Layout Limitations** | Complex layouts require workarounds | Need CSS frameworks or preprocessors |

**Examples of Limitations:**

```css
/* 1. Browser Compatibility Issues */
.element {
  /* Need vendor prefixes for older browsers */
  -webkit-transform: rotate(45deg);
  -moz-transform: rotate(45deg);
  -ms-transform: rotate(45deg);
  transform: rotate(45deg);
}

/* 2. No Parent Selector */
/* This DOESN'T work - can't select parent based on child */
/* .parent < .child { color: red; } */

/* Workaround: Use child selector instead */
.parent:has(.active-child) {
  /* Only works in modern browsers */
  background-color: yellow;
}

/* 3. Specificity Conflicts */
.button { color: blue; }           /* Specificity: 10 */
#header .button { color: red; }    /* Specificity: 110 - wins */
.button.primary { color: green; }  /* Specificity: 20 - loses */

/* 4. No Variables (before CSS custom properties) */
.header { background-color: #007bff; }
.button { background-color: #007bff; }
.footer { background-color: #007bff; }
/* Repetitive and hard to maintain */

/* Modern solution with CSS variables */
:root {
  --primary-color: #007bff;
}
.header, .button, .footer {
  background-color: var(--primary-color);
}
```

**Common Workarounds:**

```css
/* Use CSS Reset/Normalize for browser consistency */
* {
  margin: 0;
  padding: 0;
  box-sizing: border-box;
}

/* Use CSS custom properties for maintainability */
:root {
  --spacing-small: 8px;
  --spacing-medium: 16px;
  --color-primary: #007bff;
}

/* Use CSS preprocessors (Sass) for logic */
/* This would be in SCSS, not regular CSS */
/*
$primary-color: #007bff;
@mixin button-style($bg-color) {
  background-color: $bg-color;
  padding: 10px 20px;
}
*/
```

**Three Ways to Include CSS:**

| Method | Location | Priority | Use Case |
|--------|----------|----------|----------|
| **Inline CSS** | HTML element's `style` attribute | Highest | Quick fixes, dynamic styles |
| **Internal CSS** | `<style>` tag in `<head>` | Medium | Single page styles |
| **External CSS** | Separate `.css` file | Lowest | Multiple pages (recommended) |

