`transform: translate()` is significantly more performant than absolute positioning for animations and element movement.

**Performance Differences:**

**`transform: translate()` (GPU-accelerated):**
- Handled by the GPU (Graphics Processing Unit)
- Does NOT trigger layout/reflow or repaint
- Moves element in its own layer
- Ideal for animations

**Absolute positioning (CPU-bound):**
- Handled by the CPU
- Triggers layout recalculation (reflow)
- Can cause other elements to reposition
- More expensive for animations

```css
/* High performance - GPU accelerated */
.transform-move {
  transform: translateX(100px);
  transition: transform 0.3s ease;
}

.transform-move:hover {
  transform: translateX(200px);
}

/* Lower performance - triggers reflow */
.position-move {
  position: relative;
  left: 100px;
  transition: left 0.3s ease;
}

.position-move:hover {
  left: 200px;
}

/* Best practice for smooth animations */
.smooth-animation {
  will-change: transform; /* Hints browser to optimize */
  transform: translate3d(0, 0, 0); /* Force GPU layer */
}
```

**Use Cases:**
- **Transform**: Animations, hover effects, smooth transitions
- **Positioning**: Static layouts, document flow changes

**Key Rule**: Use `transform` for movement animations, `position` for layout structure.

**Feature Detection** in CSS uses the `@supports` rule to test if a browser supports specific CSS properties before applying styles. This enables progressive enhancement and graceful fallbacks.

**Basic Syntax:**
```css
@supports (property: value) {
  /* Styles applied if feature is supported */
}

@supports not (property: value) {
  /* Fallback styles for unsupported features */
}
```

**Practical Examples:**

**1. CSS Grid with Flexbox Fallback:**
```css
/* Default flexbox layout */
.container {
  display: flex;
  flex-wrap: wrap;
}

/* Grid layout for supporting browsers */
@supports (display: grid) {
  .container {
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: repeat(auto-fit, minmax(250px, 1fr));
    gap: 20px;
  }
}
```

**2. CSS Custom Properties Fallback:**
```css
.element {
  color: blue; /* Fallback */
}

@supports (--css: variables) {
  .element {
    --primary-color: #007bff;
    color: var(--primary-color);
  }
}
```

**3. Complex Feature Detection:**
```css
/* Multiple conditions with logical operators */
@supports (display: flex) and (gap: 20px) {
  .flex-container {
    display: flex;
    gap: 20px; /* Modern flexbox gap property */
  }
}

@supports not ((display: flex) and (gap: 20px)) {
  .flex-container {
    display: flex;
  }

  .flex-container > * {
    margin-right: 20px; /* Manual spacing fallback */
  }
}
```

**4. Modern CSS Features:**
```css
/* Container queries fallback */
@supports not (container-type: inline-size) {
  .card {
    width: 100%;
  }

  @media (min-width: 768px) {
    .card {
      width: 50%;
    }
  }
}

@supports (container-type: inline-size) {
  .container {
    container-type: inline-size;
  }

  @container (min-width: 400px) {
    .card {
      width: 50%;
    }
  }
}
```

**Best Practices:**
- Always provide fallbacks for newer features
- Test with older browsers that don't support `@supports`
- Use progressive enhancement approach
- Combine with JavaScript feature detection when needed
